{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_dicorcia_ver01/data/sn82016181/0052904592A/1927081501/0813.xml":{"full_text":"Gary\u2019s Life Devoted\nto Building Up the\nSteel Combine\nEntered Business Thru Legal\nOffice in West, Finally Be\ncoming Head of Company\nLEFT ENORMOUS FORTUNE\nWealth Not Known, but Was\nEstimated at $50,000,000 in\n1915; is Survived by Wife\n(Continued from Page 1)\ncoed.\nstorm.\nBut he always weathered the\nHlis labor policy was at one time\nalso under heavy fire.\nlong hours,\nHe favored\n-aying the industry\ncould not prosper without them.\nIn\nlater year his attitude softened and\nthe shortening of the hours of labor\nin the -teel industry followed.\nSuccessor Discussed\nAs to his\nsuccessor,\nWall st has\nalrrady had its fling in the last three\nyears at naming the new head of the\nSteel Corporation.\nDwight W Mor\nrow, member of J. P. Morgan Co.,\nwa: considered a year ago as in line\nfor the position.\nFormer Gov. Nathan L. Miller, of\nNew York, attorney for the steel in\nterests, was also believed\na\nlikely\nman, and within recent weeks Pierre\ndu Pont, because of his heavy inter\ne-t in the Steel Corporation, was ad\nvanced as a probable successor.\nJames F. Farrell, president of the\nSteel Corporation,\ntioned.\nwas\nalso men\nJudge Gary\nwa\none of the out\nstanding figures of all time in the\nGorki's financial history.\nHe w as\nborn Oct. X, 1846, on a farm near\nWheaton, III., anil his first work was\nthat of a farm boy.\nHe attended\nWheaton College and the Univeristy\nof Chicago.\nHis first job away from\nthe farm was as a grocery clerk at\n$12 a week.\nlatter he became a court stenog\nrapher and finally\nW as\nadmitted to\nthe Illinois bar in 1867.\nHe served two terms as a county\njudge in Dupage County, Ill.\nMoved to Chicago\nHe entered the steel business thru\nAAAOAA00/6P\n22227774Y444424(\nAnnouncing the\nOpening of\nI\nYOUNG\u2019S\ni American-Chinese\nRestaurant\n804 K St.\nWashington's\nNewest ami Fin\nest American-Chinese Resta