d many\nother financiers. Schwab made a de\nliberate speech, directed at J. P.\nMorgan,\noutlining the economies\nwhich might come to the steel in\ndustry thru amalgamation.\nIt gave\nMorgan the idea and he consulted\nGary as to. the possibility of buying\nout the Carnegie interests.\nThe announcement that the United\nStates Steel Corporation had been\nformed and a syndicate w ith a cap\nital of $200,000,000 organized to\nfinance it was made in March, 1901.1\nJudge Gary became its first presi\ndent, altho Morgan was the man be-\nhind the scenes.\nNow Dominant\nOne by one the various smaller\nSteel\nconsolidated.\ncompanies\nwere\nunder the United States Steel\nor\nganization until today it is the dom\nmating factor in the world\u2019s steel\ntrade.\nAfter a few\nas president,\nGary became chairman of the board,\nw hich\ndeath.\nposition he held until his\ni\nJudge Cary was one of the most\ninteresting characters of the finan-s\nrial world.\nHe always was optimis\ntic on America's business outlook.\nWall-st can hardly recall a pessi\nmistie statement from him.\nLiked to Have Callers\nI\nCary delighted in social visits j\nwhich friends paid to his offices and j\non these occasions would talk on a\nwide variety of subjects.\nFrequent\nly newspapermen, caling to receive\nsome\nimportant announcement,\nwould linger to hear him discuss\ntopics varying as widely as the latest\nathletic event or murder e\nand the\nFrench war debt -but he uways im\nposed silence upon them and never\npermitted his remarks to be printed.\nI hiring the last several years his\nbirthdays have been marked by in\nterviews, dealing usually with the\nlightest of subjects, and with gather\nings of friends in his offices. j\nLeaves Big Fortune\nJust what his fortune is no one to\nday could say.\nin 1913 it was esti\nmated at $50,000,000, but in the 10\nyears\nfollowing it doubled, trebled\nor even went beyond that, financiers\nsaid.\nCary\u2019s first wife, whom he mar\nried in Aurora, III., in 1869, died in\n1902.\nin\n1905 he married Emma\nTownsend, of New York, who sur\nvives him.\nNo children survive.\nStatue for Police Martyrs\nBALTIMORE\nA granite\nnynt to eight policemen killed\nduty since 1902 is beine nlan\nmoru\non\nhere.\nbeing planned j\nit would lie placed at Lex\nington st and Fallsway.\nI\nTest Answers\nare the answers\nHERE\nto the \u201cNow Y ou Ask\nOre\u201d questions on page 3.\n1. Georpe M.\n\"Over There.\u201d\nCohan wrote\n2. Jim Europe's band made\n\u201cAlexander\u2019s\nfamous.\n3. \u201cThe Long,\nRaptime Band\"\nLong Trail\"\nhad the line \"Where the night\ninpale is sinpinp and the white\nmoon beams.\"\n4. \"The Sonp of the Volga\nBoatmen\" was made the theme\nof the movie, \u201cThe Volga Boat\nmen.\u201d\n5. Victor Herbert composed\nthe music for \"The Chocolate\nSoldier\" and \"Sweetheart.\"\n6. The chorus is \u201cAin't she\nsweet, walkin' down the street;\nand let me ask you confidenti\nally. ain't she sweet?\"\n7. The\n\"Dallas Blues\" and\nthe \"Memphis Blues\" are blues\nsongs named after cities.\n8. \u201cSweet Adeline\u201d has the\nline\nAt night, dear heart, for\nyou I pine.\"\n9. \u201cYankee Doodle was first\nsung in the Revolutionary War.\n10. Stephen C. Foster wrote\n\u201cMy Old Kentucky Home.\u201d\nSoviet Editors Send Books\nto Peasants by Reindeer\nExpedition Aiwo Will show Movies\nto Isolated Siberians\nRy Uratd I'rrw\nMOSCOW Book distributors\nmounted on reindeer have set out\nfor a four months journey thru the\nSiberian province of Yaratutsk, a\nprovince larger than Erance but\nwhere travel is only possible along\nthe rivers.\nThe expedition is organized by the\nSociety of Siberian Editors to dis\ntribute books to the isolated tribes\nmen of the area.\nThe party is also\nfitted with a portable moving pic\nture projector and will show the\nnatives the first motion picture they\never have seen.\nTax Rate Won\u2019t Rise,\nDespite Budget\nThe local tax rate will not be in\ncreased thru a District budget of\n$39,500,000 for the fiscal year 1928\n29, which Budpet Director Lord and\nPresident Coolidge are believed to\nhave approved.\nThis figure, about $2,500,000 lower\nthan that a-ked by the Commis\nsioners, will tend to continue the\npresent tax rats of $1.70 for every\n$100 of ful valuation personal and\nreal property or possibly result in\na lower rate, District officials said\nThere is a strong probabil\ntoday.\nity of a $1.65 tax rate next year.\nI\nSMADEOY\nMOVING\nI\nLoeal and lasg Distance Haaliag\nMoving, P'arLiag, Mtorage\n12 K St. S. E.\nInsuraace t al\nLincoln 4282-8129\nKatimatss Gives\nried.\nRountree\u2019s Special\nSUIT CASE\nThin sult (w of Ultra Qualit, Cewhide\nwith Cowhide termers and\nM raps ail\naroued. in Brown or Kus-et. cloth lined\nwith\ninside\nexrellent Hardwai\nand\nThis\nfitted\nwith\nsperial 24-inch (ase la e\ndeed a remarkable vaue al\n$11.00\nOthers\nUp to $50.00\n1333 F St. N. W.\nFranklin 545\nTnnimarb &Uinthron\nThe Semi-Annual Selling of\nFURNITURE, RUGS, LAMPS\nAND DRAPERIES\nBegins Today\nEvery item in this Semi-Annual Event con\nforms to the Woodward Lothrop standard\nof quality and is marked at a surprisingly low\nprice. Only through careful planning, great\nreductions on regular stocks and quantity spe\ncial purchases are we able to offer such val\nues\u2014values that you must see to fully appre\nciate the splendid savings.\nTypical Items in the Selling\n3-piece Jacquard Velour Living Room Suites,\nwith reversible cushions, in colorful\ntapestry. Special.\n$185\nFurniture sertion\u2014slith Mloor\nAmerica\u2019s Best-Known, Long-Wearing Seam\nless Axminster Rugs, in new 1927\npatterns.\nThe 9x12 size.\nKug sertion\u2014Fifth I loor\n$49-50\nAlmco Bridge Lamps, with decorated metal\nbase,\nadjustable arm\nround georgette shade.\nSpecial\nand braid-trimmed,\n$16-50\nlamp sertmm\u2014peirath l leer\nSoft, Sheer Ruffled Marquisette Curtains,\nwith\nsigas\nmatching tie-backs, several de- $1-85\nin white, ivory or ecru. Pair.... 1\nCurtain S